The number of 10 seeds of each genotype was evaluated to measure the length, width and thickness of the wheat grain. For this purpose, a sliding caliper was used with an accuracy of 0.05 mm to determine the dimensions of material under study. The three linear dimensions of the grain, namely length (LEN), width (WID) and thickness (TIC) were carefully measured in mm. Protein (%), moisture (%), ZEL estimation (mL), water absorbance (mL), hardness (%) and RMT (ml/100 g flour) was determined using near-infrared reflectance (International Association for Cereal Science and Technology (ICC) standard method 159, Vienna, Austria). Solvent Retention Capacity (SRC) test was carried out according to Guzman et al. (2015) with some modification of method 56-11.02-AACC, 200044. The four standard diagnostic solvents consisted of water (WSRC), lactic acid (LASRC) (5%), sodium carbonate (SCSRC) (5%), and sucrose (SuSRC) (50%)45. In the scaled version of SRC method, 0.3 g of flour samples were placed into previously-weighed 2.0 ml tubes and suspended with 1.5 ml of each solvent using a vortex mixer. Immediately, the tubes were shaken for 5 min at 1400 rpm at room temperature (25◦C) then centrifuged at 4000 g for 2 min. After centrifugation, the supernatant was omitted and the tube was left to drain for 10 min on tissue paper. The resulting pellets were weighed and the SRC and GPI values were calculated according to Kweon et al. (2011) Eq) 1, 2)18:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
